For `locally_rightContinuous_iff`:
- The forward direction (`fun h ↦ h.rightContinuous`): If we have `Locally (fun X ↦ ∀ ω, Function.RightContinuous (X · ω)) 𝓕 X P`, then by definition, for each `ω`, the property `∀ x, ∃ l, Tendsto (fun x => X x ω) (𝓝[<] x) (𝓝 l)` holds. We need to show `∀ᵐ ω ∂P, Function.RightContinuous (X · ω)`. The definition of `Function.RightContinuous` is `∀ x, ∀ y, x < y → y ∈ nhds (f x) → f y ∈ nhds x`. This is equivalent to `∀ x, ∀ y, x < y → y ∈ nhds (f x) → f y ∈ nhds x`. The given property is `∀ x, ∃ l, Tendsto (fun x => X x ω) (𝓝[<] x) (𝓝 l)`, which means for each `x`, there exists a limit `l` such that `X x ω` tends to `l` as `x` tends to `x` from the left. This is precisely the definition of right continuity.
